The paper deals with a string matching problem and presents a solution that offers competitive space-time tradeoffs. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. The application areas mentioned in the abstract, such as online catalogs, web searchers, etc., suggest that the paper could also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) category. The paper also mentions a compression technique for DNA data, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Mining (cs.DM) category. The use of the Dirichlet principle suggests that the paper could belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) category. Finally, the implementation in the C++ language and the focus on data compaction suggest that the paper could also belong to the Databases (cs.DB) category.
